[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] By making the regions infinitessimally small, the factor relating the two densities is the ratio of volumes, which we term the **differential volume ratio**.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] To obtain concrete formulas for volume on the m -dimensional manifold, we construct U by mapping an m -dimensional rectangle in (local) coordinate space to the manifold via a smooth embedding function: $\mathbb {R} ^{m}\to \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ .
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] At very small scale, the embedding function becomes essentially linear so that U is a parallelotope (multidimensional generalization of a parallelogram).
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] Similarly, the flow transform, f becomes linear, so that the image, $V=f(U)$ is also a parallelotope.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] In $\mathbb {R} ^{m}$ , we can represent an m -dimensional parallelotope with an $m{\text{-by-}}m$ matrix whose column-vectors are a set of edges (meeting at a common vertex) that span the paralellotope.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] The volume is given by the absolute value of the determinant of this matrix.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] If more generally (as is the case here), an m -dimensional paralellotope is embedded in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , it can be represented with a (tall) $n{\text{-by-}}m$ matrix, say $\mathbf {V}$ .
