[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] In machine learning literature, various complex spherical flows formed by deep neural network architectures may be found.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] In contrast, this section compiles from *statistics* literature the details of three very simple spherical flow transforms, with simple closed-form expressions for inverses and differential volume ratios.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] These flows can be used individually, or chained, to generalize distributions on the unit sphere, $\mathbb {S} ^{n-1}$ .
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] All three flows are compositions of an invertible affine transform in $\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ , followed by radial projection back onto the sphere.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] The flavours we consider for the affine transform are: pure translation, pure linear and general affine.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] An interesting property of these simple spherical flows is that they don't make use of any non-linearities apart from the radial projection.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] Even the simplest of them, the normalized translation flow, can be chained to form perhaps surprisingly flexible distributions.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] from which we see that we need $\lVert \mathbf {c} \rVert <1$ to keep $\ell$ real and positive for all $\mathbf {y} \in \mathbb {S} ^{n-1}$ .
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] Finally, it is worth noting that $f_{\text{trans}}$ and $f_{\text{trans}}^{-1}$ do not have the same functional form.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] This result can be derived indirectly via the **Angular central Gaussian distribution (ACG)**, which can be obtained via normalized linear transform of either Gaussian, or uniform spherical variates.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] The first relationship can be used to derive the ACG density by a marginalization integral over the radius; after which the second relationship can be used to factor out the differential volume ratio.
