[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] Despite normalizing flows success in estimating high-dimensional densities, some downsides still exist in their designs.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] First of all, their latent space where input data is projected onto is not a lower-dimensional space and therefore, flow-based models do not allow for compression of data by default and require a lot of computation.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] However, it is still possible to perform image compression with them.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] Flow-based models are also notorious for failing in estimating the likelihood of out-of-distribution samples (i.e.: samples that were not drawn from the same distribution as the training set).
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] Some hypotheses were formulated to explain this phenomenon, among which the typical set hypothesis, estimation issues when training models, or fundamental issues due to the entropy of the data distributions.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] One of the most interesting properties of normalizing flows is the invertibility of their learned bijective map.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] This property is given by constraints in the design of the models (cf.: RealNVP, Glow) which guarantee theoretical invertibility.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] The integrity of the inverse is important in order to ensure the applicability of the change-of-variable theorem, the computation of the Jacobian of the map as well as sampling with the model.
[src:flow-matching/flow-matching] However, in practice this invertibility is violated and the inverse map explodes because of numerical imprecision.
[src:flow-matching/neural-ordinary-differential-equation] This approach contrasts with conventional neural networks, where information flows through discrete layers indexed by natural numbers.
[src:flow-matching/neural-ordinary-differential-equation] Neural ODEs instead use continuous layers indexed by positive real numbers, where the function $h:\mathbb {R} _{\geq 0}\to \mathbb {R}$ represents the network's state at any given layer depth *t*.
[src:flow-matching/neural-ordinary-differential-equation] Neural ODEs can be understood as continuous-time control systems, where their ability to interpolate data can be interpreted in terms of controllability.
