[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Given a cost function $c(x,y)$ , it produces a duality transformation $\psi \mapsto \psi ^{c}$ defined by $\psi ^{c}(y):=\inf _{x}(c(x,y)-\psi (x))$ This generalizes Legendre transformation, which is the case where $c(x,y)=-xy$ with a sign flip.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] We say that a function $\psi$ is ***c*-convex** if $\psi =\varphi ^{c}$ for some $\varphi$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Note that because $\varphi ^{ccc}=\varphi ^{c}$ , we can always assume that $\varphi$ is *c*-convex.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] The ***c*-convexification** of a function $\psi$ is $\psi ^{cc}$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Equivalently, it is the smallest *c*-convex function $\psi '$ such that $\psi '\geq \psi$ pointwise.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Like in the case of convex transformation, $\psi$ is *c*-convex iff $\psi =\psi ^{cc}$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] If $\psi =\varphi ^{c}:X\to \mathbb {R}$ is *c*-convex, then the set of ***c*-subdifferential** of $\psi$ at $x\in X$ is the set of $y\in Y$ such that $\psi (x)=c(x,y)-\varphi (y)$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] When $X=Y$ , the graph $(y,\psi ^{c}(y))$ can be constructed as follows: Take the graph of $\psi$ , and flip it upside down.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] At each point $(x,-\psi (x))$ , construct a graph of $y\mapsto c(x,y)$ apexed at $(x,-\psi (x))$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] That is, it is the graph of $y\mapsto c(x,y)-\psi (x)$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Their lower-edge envelope is the graph of $\psi ^{c}$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] In the same image, we can see what it means for a function $\varphi (y)$ to be *c*-convex.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] It is *c*-convex iff its entire graph can be "touched" by a "tipped tool" that is moving and shape-shifting.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] When the tipped tool is at x , it has a shape of $y\mapsto c(x,y)$ and is raised to a height of $-\psi (x)$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] The graph of the *c*-convexification $\varphi ^{cc}(y)$ is constructed by running the tipped tool so that it is lowered as much as possible, while still touching graph of $\varphi (y)$ on the upper side.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] The lower envelope swept out by the tipped tool is the graph of $\varphi ^{cc}(y)$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] For example, if $X=Y=\mathbb {R} ^{n}$ is a metric space and $c(x,y)=\|x-y\|$ , then $\varphi :X\to \mathbb {R}$ is *c*-convex iff it is 1-Lipschitz.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] This is used in the definition of 1-Wasserstein distance.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] If $c(x,y)=\|x-y\|^{2}$ , then $\varphi$ is *c*-convex iff its graph could be touched from above by a tipped tool with the shape of a paraboloid.
