[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] The optimal transport problem has an economic interpretation.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] In the interpretation, the duality transformation transforms a loading cost function $\varphi (x)$ into the optimal (for the shipper) unloading cost function $\psi (y)=\varphi ^{c}(y)$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] If the unloading cost function $\psi (y)$ were any higher at any point, then there would be some route $x\to y$ on which $c(x,y)<\varphi (x)+\psi (y)$ , meaning that there is some route on which you would rather ship yourself.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] But if the unloading cost function were any lower at any point, then the shipper could have earned more money by raising the price there.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Therefore, the shipper should always choose $\psi =\varphi ^{c}$ .
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Assume that the shipper in fact must pay the same cost function and us, and can exactly reach the maximum revenue using $(\varphi ,\psi )$ as their pricing chart.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Then the shipper must use an optimal plan, at which point the shipper just breaks even with no profit.
[src:flow-matching/optimal-transport] Conversely, any shipping plan that allows the shipper to exactly break even must be optimal.
