[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] Some differential equations have solutions that can be written in an exact and closed form.
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] Several important classes are given here.
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] In the table below, $P(x)$ , $Q(x)$ , $P(y)$ , $Q(y)$ , and $M(x,y)$ , $N(x,y)$ are any integrable functions of x , y ; b and c are real given constants; $C_{1},C_{2},\ldots$ are arbitrary constants (complex in general).
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] The differential equations are in their equivalent and alternative forms that lead to the solution through integration.
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] When all other methods for solving an ODE fail, or in the cases where we have some intuition about what the solution to a DE might look like, it is sometimes possible to solve a DE simply by guessing the solution and validating it is correct.
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] To use this method, we simply guess a solution to the differential equation, and then plug the solution into the differential equation to verify whether it satisfies the equation.
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] If it does then we have a particular solution to the DE, otherwise we start over again and try another guess.
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] For instance we could guess that the solution to a DE has the form: $y=Ae^{i\alpha t}$ since this is a very common solution that physically behaves in a sinusoidal way.
[src:flow-matching/ordinary-differential-equation] In the case of a first order ODE that is non-homogeneous we need to first find a solution to the homogeneous portion of the DE, otherwise known as the associated homogeneous equation, and then find a solution to the entire non-homogeneous equation by guessing.
